    <h1 class="article-title">The Slow Destruction: How Iron Turns to Rust</h1>
    <p class="article-desc">Explore the fascinating oxidation reaction that transforms shiny iron into flaky, reddish-brown rust through its interaction with oxygen and water in our environment.</p>
    <div class="meta">8 min read · Includes video · 3 research links</div>
  </div>

  <div class="section-label">The reaction</div>
  <div class="equation-box">
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#AFA9EC;">4Fe + 3O₂ + 6H₂O</span>
    <span class="eq-arrow">→</span>
    <span class="eq-part" style="color:#9FE1CB;">4Fe(OH)₃</span>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">Every time you see a rusty nail, a corroded car bumper, or the reddish-brown flakes on an old iron fence, you're witnessing the aftermath of one of the most common chemical reactions on Earth. The rusting of iron is a slow but relentless process that has been shaping our world for millions of years, long before humans discovered how to work with metals.</p>
  
  <p class="body-text">Rusting is essentially iron's way of returning to its natural state. Pure iron rarely exists in nature—instead, we find iron ores like hematite (Fe₂O₃) and magnetite (Fe₃O₄). When we extract pure iron and shape it into useful objects, we're fighting against nature's preference for iron to be oxidized. Rust is iron's inevitable journey back to an oxidized form, similar to what it was before we refined it.</p>

  <div class="callout">
    <div class="callout-title">Why Does Iron Need Both Oxygen AND Water to Rust?</div>
    <div class="callout-text">Pure iron exposed to completely dry oxygen will not rust significantly. Similarly, iron submerged in oxygen-free water won't rust either. The rusting process requires both oxygen and water because it involves multiple steps: iron atoms lose electrons (oxidation) to oxygen molecules, while water molecules help facilitate the electron transfer and provide hydroxide ions that combine with the iron to form iron hydroxide—what we call rust.</div>
  </div>

  <p class="body-text">The rusting process actually happens in stages. First, iron atoms at the surface lose electrons to become iron ions (Fe²⁺). These electrons are picked up by oxygen molecules dissolved in water, which then combine with hydrogen ions to form more water molecules. The iron ions then react with hydroxide ions in the water to form iron(II) hydroxide, which further oxidizes in the presence of more oxygen to become iron(III) hydroxide—the reddish-brown substance we recognize as rust. This is why rust appears to "grow" and spread over time, as the reaction continues to consume more iron from within the metal.</p>

